tify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This spirit of collaboration is reflected in the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">City Centred</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> campaign which was launched in September 2013 and has brought together the Mayor, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">London Councils, and the Core Cities Group to jointly campaign for fiscal and wider devolution to England’s cities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">London’s population is equivalent to those of Scotland and Wales combined. Its economy is almost double the size of these nations together</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">By 2030, London’s population will have grown to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">10</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> million people; its economy, also, is </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">expected </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to grow faster than most other UK regions. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">As this growth continues, massi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ve investment in infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, both physical and social</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, will be required </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to acc</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ommodate the city’s resi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">dents and commuters. To do this</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> as well as to pro</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">mote additional economic growth</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> London government must be enabled to invest more in its own infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to benefit financially from the fiscal uplift</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in which</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> its investments </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and policies result</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and to take greater responsibility for its own affairs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In stark comparison to many other major global cities, London relies </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">heavily </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">on central government for the majority of its revenues</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. Barely 7</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> per cent</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of all the tax paid by Lond</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">on’s residents and businesses is retained by the M</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ayor </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and the b</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">oroughs</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. The equivalent figure in New York is 50</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> per cent. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">espite the growing dynamic towards Scottish and Welsh devolution, England remains </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">centralised</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> country</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Something needs to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">done</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and i</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">t is the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> view</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the proposals made by the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">LFC</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to devolve all property ta</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">xes to London government would be an appropriate way of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rebalancing the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">relationship </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">between central and city government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">support of the need to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">promote</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">economic growth,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">line with </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">other great international cities</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in a way that </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">is being shown</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> feasible in other parts of the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Executive summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> response is informed by the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">work</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">LFC</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, which</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> reported to the Mayor in May 2013 and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> made the following overarching recommendation:</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">London government should have the freedom to make appropriate investments in its own infrastructure both to cater for the growth already forecast for its population and economy, and to promote additional eco</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">nomic growth. Relaxing restrictions on borrowing for capital investment within prudential rules and devolving revenue streams, including from the full suite of property taxes, will afford London government the autonomy to invest in the capital and increase</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> its accountability to London’s residents and businesses, without affecting the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">financial settlements of other parts of the country</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">consider</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">that the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">fiscal </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">powers</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> recommended by the LFC </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">should operate within the Greater London boundary and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">within the existing institutional</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> framework</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of the GLA and the London boroughs. The powers and responsibilities of the different sections of London government should be clearly distinguished and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> where possible</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the need for joint decision making </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">about fis</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">cal matters </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">limited </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to ensure simplicity, transparency and accountability</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> are maintained or increased</span><span style="font-famil