nt</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and therefore </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">result in</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> growth. It wo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">uld be for London government to decide how and when to introduce</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">reforms.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">After the point of devolution the Treasury </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">sh</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> have no role in the collection or redistribution of London’s property taxes or newly created taxes</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> – particularly not for </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">additional </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">growth -</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">it w</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> be necessary to develop </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a mechanism </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to ring fence Lo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">on’s remaining grant allocation. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The rest of the country would not be put at a disadvan</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">tage by devolution to London. The Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> consider</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the potential for distortio</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ns at the border insignificant, and changes </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">sh</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ould be met with a pound-for-pound reduction in grant at the outset.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Under the Mayor’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> proposal</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s, it is</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> estimate</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> that the Treasury would still control approximately 88 per cent of the overall tax base.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Mayor believes similar arrangements would work in other UK cities, and the purpose of the joint </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">City Centred </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">campaign with the Core Cities is to make the case for city devolution.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Part 1: Concept</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How ‘devolved’ areas would be de</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">fined geographically and s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">et up</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Devo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">lution to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> London government would not require geographical redefinition. Powers </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would be divided between the GLA a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">nd </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> London</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> boroughs as appropriate (see point</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">6 – 17</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">below).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How public services, including employment, skills and welfare, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">should be org</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">anised to complement devolution</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It is important to make a clear distinction between the devolution of public service delivery to London government and the devolution of fiscal powers</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. Only the l</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">atter was considered by the LFC; it</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> did not look</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> into how devolved funds should be used</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The London Enterprise Panel (LEP) is developing </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">options</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">devolved skills, employment and housing powers for the London boroughs as part of the Government’s Growth Deal agenda</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. It will submit its final proposals</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to Government in spring 201</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> The Cities Growth Commission is </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">considering devolu</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">tion of public service delivery,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and the GLA is supporting its work. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">support</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the extension of ‘single pot’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> or Commu</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">nity Budget schemes in London, and if fisc</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">al powers are devolved it may be possible for the GLA to work with boroughs and groups of boroughs to create ‘City Deal’-type initiatives within London.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How ‘devolved’ areas would be governed, including the role</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> of business in decision making</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ny decisions about governance will depend on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the powers</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> actually</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> devolved.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Definitive political agreement about the division of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">such </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">powers between different sections of Londo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">n government </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">cannot be reached until </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">trilateral </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">negotiations have taken place between </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">local, city and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">central government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> However, for the purposes of this </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">response</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> will work to the assumption that the LFC’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> recommendations will be enacted in full.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In the Mayor’s view, a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ny system to govern </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">new tax raising powers should be as simple as possible. The responsibilities of the GLA and the separate London boroughs should be distinguished clearly from the outset. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In the interests of simplicity, transparency and accountability, where possible</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the sy</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">stem should </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">limit</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the need for joint decisions to be made between different sections of London government. The existing governance apparatus in London and current responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> as divided between the different </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">sections of London government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> will remain</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in place. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">For the avoidance of doubt, this does not in any way preclude joint working in a number of areas, which takes place in practice already</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Regardle</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ss of the model taken forward, the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">take</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> seriously the recommendations of the LFC </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ratepayers should be protected from unreasonably high rate increases</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> believe</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> there is genuine scope to improve business engagement. By strengthening the link between </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">local </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">tax and spending, the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> hope</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> that business views about </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">policy an</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">d spending to promote</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> growth </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and create</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> a clement business environment </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">will feature more prominently in local government discourse</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (though obviously revenues from business rates and other property taxes will continue to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">fund vital core local government </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">services</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, as well as activities relating to economic development</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">intend</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">involve</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> business groups</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> when</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> develop</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> credible options</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">for appropriate</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> consultation </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">mechanisms. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How ‘devolved’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> areas would be held to account</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">At present, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">GLA decisions are </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">formally </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">scrutinised by the London Assembly</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, which already has the power to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">amend the Mayor’s annual budget and to amend Mayoral strategies</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The LFC report suggests that </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">if </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">devolution occurs, it may be appropriate to review the Assembly’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> powers</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> with a view to enhancing them. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">agree</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> with this premise, and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">will want to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">assist Government, the Committee, the Assembly and other stakeholders in considering the Assembly’s role within the context </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of fiscal devolution to the GLA.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Aside </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">from institutional </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">scrutiny</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> mechanisms, i</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">n any democratic system</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the electorate</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> al</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">so plays a key role in holding</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> government to account</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. A clear failing of the existing system, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in our view,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> is that the perception of many voters that council tax alone funds all local government services belies the reality of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">substantial reliance on national government for funding. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The system is therefore not sufficiently transparent or accountable to taxpayer</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, and is unusual compared to many other OECD countries</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (see Annex </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The LFC’s recommendations were based on principles of good governance, including accountability (strengthening the link between spending decisions and taxes raised, such that the impac</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">t of tax and spending decisions is clear to local taxpayers), transparency (to improve taxpayers’ understanding of the system) and autonomy (such that local government can make meaningful decisions about how much to spend on what).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The strength of the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">evidence that devolution would lead to economic growth, local improvement and better local governance, including examples of what areas could do with their new powers such as use them to invest in in</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">frastructure and local services</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Economic </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">g</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rowth</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The balance of evidence, including from written submissions to the LFC, work commissioned by the LFC, evidence from the impact of the limited number of fiscal freedoms that London has won, a survey of the academic literature, and the Government’s own appra</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">isal of its 2011 business rate reforms indicates that a modicum of fiscal devolution should support growth. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">As detailed in the LFC report, the body of academic evidence about the effects of decentralisation on economic growth is inconclusive</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> that is to say that some studies show positive effects on growth, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">some negative and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> some neutral.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">it is very likely that the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">economic </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">growth will be driven by London </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and other major cities</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in the coming decades, there are a number of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">reasons that the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> believe</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> fiscal devolution will </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">enable London government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to accommodate economic (and population) growth and to promote </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">additional</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> economic</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">growth, building on successful examples of local growth initiatives driven by London </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">government, such as the Northern Line Extension</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (which will be funded through a TIF mechanism)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, the business rate supplement </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">which has part funded Crossrail</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and the council tax precept </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">which helped fund </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the Olympics).</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">New arrangements</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> would afford London government greater certainty about its own available funds, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">which would allow for more efficient use of project resources and better procurement planning, and avoid unnecessary costs, such as those relating to abortive </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">capital </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">projects</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">Devolving property taxes (and removing borrowing ceilings, while retaining prudential rules) would allow the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">GLA </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">prudentially </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">borrow </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">to make more</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">capital investment</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">. Over time, such investment in productive assets</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">would </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">develop the city’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">s economy</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> and provide financial returns to local government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">In this way, devolvi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">ng property taxes would </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">act as a financial incentive for </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">local government to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">grant permission for large developments.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 19.85pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-19.85pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">At present the granting of tax increment financing (TIF) schemes </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">relies on central gove</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">rnment decision making, which the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> view</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> as too restrictive, whereas under the proposed arrange</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">ments, London government would</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> have greater flexibility to promote </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">growth in this way. For example the GLA and boroughs could agree ar</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">eas or zones within London suitable for TIF projects, such as a cross boundary area where, for a period of time, the additional revenues from property taxes would be used to repay borrowings for the capital investment in a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">certain project (eg a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">new station</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt"> required to generate these incremental taxes.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It is possible that engaging more with business could result in local investments that promote economic development (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">following the precedent of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">London </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">business community</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’s agreement to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the Crossrail</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> business rate supplement), or a m</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ore </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">benign</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> business tax regime that favours growth.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The scope for reform</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of property taxes (particularly SDLT) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">at the London level that fiscal devolution would </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">create could also prom</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ote growth. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The property tax system </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">operation </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">at present</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> has developed over time in an illogical and piecemeal way, r</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">esulting in an imperfect system. Of all property taxes, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">SDLT is considered one of the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">worst designed; a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ccording to the Mirrlees</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Review, it is ‘highly inefficient, discouraging mobility and meaning that properties are not held by the people who value them most, and its ‘slab’ structure—with big cliff-edges in tax payable at certain thresholds—creates particularly perverse incentive</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s.’</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">These n</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">egative effects are </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">amplified</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in London because of the unique and high-value character of its property market</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (in 201</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">2/13</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, approximately </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">41 </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">per cent of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">all residential </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">UK SDLT was collected in London, and approximately </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">58</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> per cent of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">all SDLT c</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ollected on properties worth over £500k</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The case for reform</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> is therefore compelling, and the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> believe</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> it would best be conducted at the local level in order to reflect and react to local property circumstances. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">If SDLT were devolved, the GLA could</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> choose to reduce, abolish or otherwise reform it</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (eg by smoothing out cliff-edge thresholds), </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">such that </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">London’s property market </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would become more economically efficient</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and more growth would therefore occur.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#376092; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Local improvement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The congestion charge, a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> GLA initiative, has set a promising precedent for local autonomy result</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ing in tangible policy outcomes, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in this case eased traffi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">c flow and improved air quality</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">If fiscal powers are devolved, London government could improve other services by spending </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">according to local ne</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ed, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">planning ahead more effectively</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and implementing fiscal policy levers</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">If </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">additional powers were devo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">lved, as being proposed in the Growth D</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">eal,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the London boroughs, supported by the GLA and the LEP, w</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ould </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">be able to deliver more </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">innovative and locally suited services in housing, skills and employment.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Local governance</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> strong democratic argument exists in favour of strengthe</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ning the link between local tax </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and spending. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">As such, it is our view that fiscal devolution to London would </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">increas</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e accountability and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> transparency </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to voters, which </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in itself would improve local governance.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The LFC report cites a study by Professor Andres Rodri</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">guez-Pose and colleagues</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">suggests that general satisfaction with government can increase as a result of devolution, if the actual capacity of local government to deliver is augmented</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The impact on areas not included in any new devolution arrangements, including those on cities</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">’ borders and those affected by resulting changes to national financial equalisation an</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">d distributive arrangements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Impact on city borders</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">During its policy development process, the LFC considered the consequences of devolved taxes at the border. Its </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">deliberations took account of a well-balanced report conducted by the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Institute on Municipal Finance and Government at the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> University of Toronto</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, which explored the pros and cons of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">operati</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> taxes</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> locally</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and drew the overall conclusion that property tax</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">es are generally well-suited to local operation</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (property taxes are under local control in New York, Frankfurt, Madrid, Paris and Berlin), </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">unlike</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> taxes with mobile bases such as sales taxes, local variations to which can cause significant distortions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Small variations in property tax rates would constitute </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">one of many other </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">factor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s that affect the decisions of businesses and residents to locate in a particular area, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">including public service provision and the impact of aggl</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">omeration, and as such the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> consider</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> them acceptable. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Changes to national financial equalisation and distributive arrangements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The devolution of property taxes to London government, as proposed by the LFC, would be met at the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">outset with a pound-for-pound reducti</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">on in grant</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, in line with the changes that were made for all local authorities in 2013-14 to take account of the partial retention of business rates. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">As such, it would have no effect on the finances of other parts of the cou</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ntry at the point of devolution (though t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> changes would follow</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the model of the business rate reforms, which were intended to produce different financial effects from place to place as a r</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">esult of their incentive </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">effect)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">believes</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> fiscal devolution would encourage London government </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">promote additional growth</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">see points </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">23</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">31</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">above</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">). If it were successful in this regard,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Lon</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">don </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would retain the uplift in devolved property tax revenues</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (to be reinvested in productive ways</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, see points </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">25 to 28</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">above</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">but central government would </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">collect and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> redistribute the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">full sum, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">including the related </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">uplift</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> all other tax revenues (</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">such as</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> income tax and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> corporation tax), which make up by far the majority of overall tax revenues </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">(around 88 per cent</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, according to our estimates</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Whether </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">reform of the existing system (for example, re-banding council tax, revaluing business rates, Community Budgets</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, Government grants, formulas and taxes</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> such as stamp duty) would be a precursor to, or run along with, large-scale constitutional change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">efor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">m of the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">property tax </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">system</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">which might include </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">conducting a revaluation of the property tax base</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> introducing new council tax bands</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> or</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> removing cliff-edge SDLT </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">thresholds</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> not</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> be a straightforward endeavour, given</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the multiplicity of actors and st</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">akeholders</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> at play in</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> London’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s property tax landscape</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would require thorough consultation and enquiries into the effects on intra-London grant </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">formulas and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">dis</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">tribution and tax equalisation,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">which would take place after </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">point of devolution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">our view, inaction is likely to prevail unless</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> legislative</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> provision is made to counter it</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">; such provisions could require periodic review (and reforms if subsequently recommended) by London government of the tax system within particular time periods.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Part</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> 2: Details</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What taxes might be devolved—for example council tax</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, stamp duty and business rates</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> accept</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">evidence-based </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">recommendations of the LFC that ‘the full suite of property taxes (council tax, business rates, stamp duty, annual tax on</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> enveloped dwellings and capital gains property development tax) should be devolved to London government which should have devolved responsibility for setting the tax rates and authority over all matters including revaluation, banding and discounts.'</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This would afford London government control of approximately </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">£12bn per year (an additional £5bn beyond existing council tax revenues and retained business rates).</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Trilateral discussions between central, city and local government would result in agreement a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">bout which grants should be replaced by devolved revenues.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">hat changes should be made to “devolved</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">” authorities’ borrowing powers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">To complement </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">fiscal powers, GLA borrowing ceilings should be removed </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">along with</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Government borrowing</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> limits and other HMT controls</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, though the Prudential Code should remain in place. This would allow the GLA </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to borrow as much as it c</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> prudently afford to make capital investments, which in time would produce a higher level of tax, from which both London and national government would benefit</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The same should apply to the London boroughs, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">including </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">for housing purposes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he scope for a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">reas to introduce new taxes and funding methods such as bonds and crowd-sourcing, fees and charges</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Permissive legislation should allow t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he GLA and London boroughs </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to introduce smaller new taxes, subject to suitable </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and robust </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">consultation. Potential new </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">taxes</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> may</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> include a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">hotel bedroom</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> tax, revenues from which might be used to improve the public realm and for international promotion, and an undeveloped land tax, which could be a useful policy lever to incentivise development and promote growth. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Whereve</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">r possible, fees and charges should be determined locally and the ability to recover full costs should be built into the system. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In the longer term, London government should be responsible for administering any introduction of road charging that may replac</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e vehicle excise duty, and yields should be retained locally.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It should be for t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he Mayor and London’s local authorities </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">determine which </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">TIF</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> projects</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> with which</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to proceed</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">As part of the GLA’s ongoing work on </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a London</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Infrastructure Investment Plan</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">new sources of funding and financing </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">that could be used for capital investment are being </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">examined</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he extent to which high-performing areas would be expected to redistribute their proc</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">eeds of growth via the Treasury</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">All London property tax revenues </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">should be retained by London government</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">sh</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ould not be redistributed by the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Treasury. While there would be an offset in grant</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> at the outset</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (except for any smaller new taxes introduced)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, it is important</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to ensure that London’s remaining grant allocation is ring-fenced </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">at least for a period of time </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to protect it against automatic </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">claw</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">back of resources </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">by central government </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">through diminished grant settlements in future if additional growth in the propert</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">y tax base</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> is created</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">such moves</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> would erode London’s autonomy and negate any incent</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ive effects of proposed changes.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> In the longer run it is recognised that if London succeeded financially as a result of this reform it might increase the momentum towards </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">further devolution of services. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It would be for London government to decide if and how intra-London equalisation </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and changes to grant formulas </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">should work, and it is likely </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">any changes</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> would be informed by detailed technical enquiries.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">All other tax revenues, including the uplift in revenues linked to London’s growth, would be collected and redistributed by the Treasury, though </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in line</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> wi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">th the LFC's recommendations, the Mayor is</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> keen to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">explore </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">how </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">more radical approaches to building </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">centives for London government into the tax system, similar to those proposed for Greater Manchester</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in the ‘Earn Back’ scheme</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">could function </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in London </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">alongside devolved property taxes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Having accepted all the recommendations of the LFC, the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Mayor and London Councils have </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">joined the Core Cities in the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">City Centred</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> campaign, the purpose of which is to influence decision makers and ensure that all main party manifestoes</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> for the 2015 General Election</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> include commitments to city devolution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Mayor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> invite</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the Committee to consider our recommendations for action by the Government and other decision makers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Annex </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This table is taken from the LFC report </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Raising the Capital, p25</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5.65pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5.65pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">Taxation revenue attributable to sub-national and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.05pt">central/federal government as a percentage of GDP, 2010</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr style="height:3pt"><td style="background-color:#ffffff; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding:4pt 4pt 5.65pt; vertical-align:top; width:62.35pt"><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5.65pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family: