</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Existing areas of collaboration include local transport schemes, public realm improvements, skills and employment programmes, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">ri-borough arrangements, open data and smart cities, crime prevention and working through the LEP.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Still, the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> consider</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Professor Henry Overman’s research about the incentive effect of the devolved business rate, which formed the basis of CLG’s ret</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">ained business rate policy, of particular relevance to the situation in Lon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">don. As its focus was London, the Mayor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> also take</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> seriously the conclusion of the research conducted by the University of Toronto for the LFC (see p5 for reference), that ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">London w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">ould benefit from greater fiscal autonomy – access to a mix of taxes and the ability to set the tax rates.’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Mirrlees Review, Tax by Design, Chapter 20, p12. Also see Mirrlees Review, Dimensions of Tax Design, Chapter 8.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a n